    <text>
        <body>
            <head>81. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d81fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Staff Material, <placeName
                        corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName>, Subject File, Box 61,
                        <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>: 2/77–12/78.
                    Limited Official Use. Drafted by <persName corresp="rec5w1npIkzy0ckLU"
                        >Weislogel</persName>; cleared by <persName corresp="recqQ6Wv2eONUThFu"
                        >Atherton</persName> and in EB/AVP, L/<gloss target="#t_PM_1">PM</gloss>,
                        <gloss target="#t_PM_1">PM</gloss>/ISO, <gloss target="#t_INR_1"
                    >INR</gloss>/DDC, and L/EB; approved by <persName corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg"
                        >Habib</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-02-13T02:37:00+00:00">February 13, 1977, 0237Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>32744. Subject: Protest to <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                Over <orgName corresp="rechTQoxKKZzt2GDZ">Navy</orgName> Aircraft Incident.<note
                    n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d81fn2">An unknown hand underlined the subject
                    line.</note> Ref: Tripoli 196.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d81fn3">In
                    telegram 196 from Tripoli, February 9, the Embassy wrote: “Our most recent
                    information from <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName>
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="receEP5YJv8hHaXra">civilian aviation</rs> (pouched
                        <gloss target="#t_NEAAFN_1">NEA/AFN</gloss>) indicates that <gloss
                        target="#t_LARG_1">
                        <orgName corresp="rec0DjV1UIFMpMgBG">LARG</orgName>
                    </gloss> has established two danger areas and two restricted areas within the
                    sea area of the Tripoli FIR. Incident occurred outside these areas. We not aware
                    that <gloss target="#t_LARG_1">
                        <orgName corresp="rec0DjV1UIFMpMgBG">LARG</orgName>
                    </gloss> claims control over any other areas off Tripoli. Please advise whether
                    we should pursue matter of restricted air space off Tripoli.” (National
                    Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D770046–0510)</note>
            </p>
            <p>1. <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department</orgName> not repeat not prepared
                to allow <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> assertion of
                prohibited zone over <rs type="topic" corresp="recwXdagbfSBlXglR">international
                    waters</rs> to go unchallenged. Accordingly, Embassy is instructed to deliver
                following note to <gloss target="#t_MFA_1">MFA</gloss>.</p>
            <p>2. Begin text: The Embassy of the United States of America refers to the Ministry’s
                note of February 7, 1977, concerning the encounter between a United States <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="reclDWPzWLFcH99Zg">military aircraft</rs> and <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> Air Force planes on January
                    27.<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d81fn4">See <ref target="#d79fn2">footnote
                        2, Document 79</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>3. The U.S. aircraft at no time approached closer than 53 nautical miles from the
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> coast and at the time
                it was intercepted by the <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName>
                planes was 75 nautical miles off <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libyan</placeName> shores. The U.S. considers that the American aircraft in
                question was exercising the freedom to fly over the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec1ldfvh0EmC9PyC">high seas</rs> in accordance with <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recvMZKA8yxNgdF29">international law</rs>. The United States does not
                consider that any nation may validly purport to subject any part of the <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="rec1ldfvh0EmC9PyC">high seas</rs>, or the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recgO0zWiwmY4SEHo">airspace</rs> over the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec1ldfvh0EmC9PyC">high seas</rs>, to its sovereignty, nor to establish
                prohibited areas of the kind referred to in the Ministry’s note. Moreover, the
                    <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> considers that the aircraft of the <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> Air Force that flew dangerously
                close to the American aircraft failed to pay reasonable regard to the interests of
                all states in the exercise of the freedom of the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec1ldfvh0EmC9PyC">high seas</rs>, in accordance with <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recvMZKA8yxNgdF29">international law</rs>.<note n="5" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d81fn5">An unknown hand highlighted the first three sentences of this
                    paragraph.</note>
            </p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Vance</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
